Four stars are pretty high in my book to give to a or any restaurant. A better or more accurate analysis depends on more data or high frequency of visitsin this case. In other words one shall not rate a place, person or business per one or two visits or experiences. I have been to this restaurant about 7-8 times so far and I find their food to be authentic, quality and tasteful. Their goat-karahi is better than most and samosa-chaat is really authentic. In appetizers category, Fish-Pakora is my favorite. Their service could be lagging so either order over the phone before arriving and reserving a table or be ready for a slow service with infrequent waiter/ess visits to your table. Environment is good enough to be between a good Italian sit in and a takeout. Furniture is not too comfortable but decent enough. Oh and their Chai (both regular and Kashmiri) are unique and good. I am guilty of being a spoiled brat regarding goooood food from a family & friends full of cooks, thus hard to impress. And wrote this one as a payback to reviewer community as I utilize their reviews on Google and elsewhere many times. U r welcome:)

Before trying any new restaurant, I'm sure all of us often check it out online to see what other people have said about it. When my dad suggested Al-Nawaab, the first thing I did was yelp it. 2 and a half stars... my immediate reaction was to go oh hellllll nah. 2 and a half stars does not sound like a place worth going. But we were already almost outside (we were in the neighborhood) so we're like sigh, whatever, we'll give it a try based on word of mouth recommendations. My experience in comparison to the reviews I read: SERVICE: Okay, yes. I totally see how they could step up their service. However, I didn't think it was much of a problem if you decide to step back a little and consider that a lot of other desi places are also run in a very similar, casual manner. For example, we had to get up and get our own drinks from the fridges, request our own cups and go to the front to tell the lady we were ready to order before she quickly came over to our table. I guess at a more traditional restaurant you'd expect a waitress/waiter to pay more attention and be at your service but that's just not the vibe I got from this place. Maybe it's because we were a smaller party or maybe it's because our food was served relatively quickly, but I didn't think it was that much of a problem. Just kind of a lack of organization, which could certainly be frustrating for a customer when the restaurant is busier or they have come with a large group. FOOD: So they have some food items at the front of the restaurant that are already ready, and I think they just warm them up and serve. We had the daal from there and honestly is was SO GOOD. Normally I'd be super turned off about the fact that I'm not eating fresh food, but it was VERY good. Aside from that, we ordered chicken handi (basically karahi, it was okay), chicken boti (I forgot which specifically, it was eh), fish tandoori (very good), gol gappe (had to make them yourself which might be annoying to some people) and a zinger burger (actually pretty decent. Not filling though). Could I see myself going here again? Honestly, yes. The place was clean, the food was decent, the service was passable. Definitely not a 5 star restaurant but I do think it has a LOT of potential.
